Crippling Overspecialization|Each noble has their strengths and weaknesses, which you can often exploit: The Knight likes to create lots of armies and send them into battles frequently, but his domestic skill is very poor, with bad economy and over-reliance on wooden palisade castles. On higher difficulties, it's possible for him to be permanently stuck on one county as his rapidly-built armies are unable to conquer any neutral towns. The Bishop fields large armies and prefers to build as many top-tier royal castles as possible. But he has a tendency to overexpand, and his armies have a huge ratio of peasants that will be easily cut down by real soldiers. Though assaulting his castles can be a hassle, taking out his armies and counties that don't have a built castle can be easy if you can get to it before the castle is built. The Baron is a cautious and defensive economist. He takes time building up his counties, so if you can take him out early, he's a pushover. But if you let him build up his counties and armies, he can be quite a threat. The Countess is a mix of the other lords, averaging out to an aggressive expansionist with a good economy. She can sometimes overexpand much like the Bishop, but she relies heavily on the weaker Motte and Bailey castle, making her lands vulnerable to being cut in half. Her armies often contain a mix of troops, including crossbows, making her more dangerous than the other nobles if left alone for too long.|Lords of the Realm|1994|VideoGame|https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/LordsOfTheRealm2
